urlhtml: St Mary-at-Lambeth Church - Museum of Garden History
title: St Mary-at-Lambeth Church - Museum of Garden History
description:
The Garden Museum, formerly known as the Museum of Garden History, is based in the deconsecrated parish church of St Mary-at-Lambeth adjacent to Lambeth Palace.
St Mary-at-Lambeth Church is mentioned in the Domesday Book as being owned by Countess Goda, sister of Edward the Confessor. The Bishops of Rochester were later given the living, which in 1197 passed to the Archbishops of Canterbury. The church was rebuilt in the 1370s and again in the late 15th and early 16th centuries. Philip Hardwick the Younger rebuilt the church in 1851-2 to match the tower. The church was badly damaged in the Second World War and was restored by Godfrey Allen. The church was taken over by The Tradescant Trust as the first museum of garden history in the UK. British naval officer William Bligh is buried in the churchyard behind the church.

https://londonchurchbuildings.wordpress.com/2014/11/15/st-mary-albert-embankment-lambeth-former-now-the-museum-of-garden-history/

title: Victoria Station House
description:
An 8-storey office building originally built in 1868 by the Metropolitan District Railway Company when they first opened an underground railway station here, although since much modernised. The ground floor and beneath remains today a ticket hall giving immediate access to the Circle & District Line Platforms of Victoria Underground Station, and which lie immediately beneath Terminus Place. 

Although Windsor House, a 19-storey post-modern office tower block located a little further to the east along Victoria Street http://old.wikimapia.org/#lat=51.4970503&lon=-0.1372513&z=18&l=0&m=b&v=8&show=/4623733/Windsor-House  remains the main administrative headquarters building for Transport for London, the modern London Transport Authority which has assumed the responsibilities of the former London Underground, it maintains offices here at Victoria Station House dedicated to its underground services.

Address:    London Underground Ltd., Victoria Station House
            191 Victoria Street, London SW1E 2NE
Telephone:  0345 020 0015
Email:      vsu@tube.tfl.gov.uk

title: Pimlico Tube Station
description:
Much like any other tube station.  It is the nearest stop to Tate Britain, and in the summer months a stream of tourists, much like ants, make their way there and back.
The building directly above (outlined in the box) is currently being refurbished for Government use.  

Elizabeth David (nee Gwynne), the celebrity chef who brought mediterranean food products and cooking to the English diet after WW2 had a cookery shop in Pimlico from 1965.  A sign of how bad things were then was that olive oil was considered as medication in England at that time, not a food.

title: St. Saviours Church
description:
St. Saviours is one of the most popular churches in the Pimlico area with a large congregation made up of people from across the social spectrum. The actual building is a wonderful construction and has been carefully crafted with a great deal of attention being spent on both the stonework and the magnificent stained glass windows. The church stands close to Pimlico Station and is popular with commuters and residents alike.
